76
00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:27.310
All right. So it is a great honor to be here and share one of our recent studies,

77
00:04:27.940 --> 00:04:31.740
which is on Chromatin remodeler CHD7 drives lineage plasticity

78
00:04:32.300 --> 00:04:35.680
and modulates replication competence in neuroendocrine prostate cancer.

79
00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:41.000
So neuroendocrine prostate cancer, or NEPC, is an aggressive subtype of advanced

80
00:04:41.060 --> 00:04:44.780
prostate cancer that often emerges following androgen receptor pathway inhibition.

81
00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:49.540
Its incidence has been increasing over the years and now accounts for up to 20% of

82
00:04:49.580 --> 00:04:50.480
the late-stage disease.

83
00:04:51.740 --> 00:04:55.640
In contrast to the initial prostatic adenocarcinoma, which depends

84
00:04:55.720 --> 00:04:58.840
on the AR signaling, NEPC cells often undergo lineage

85
00:04:58.920 --> 00:05:02.360
plasticity by losing dependence on the AR signaling and

86
00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:06.400
relapse with an acquisition of a neuroendocrine phenotype, and therefore

87
00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:08.420
resistance to the conventional pathway inhibition.

88
00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:12.070
Current treatment options for NEPC are still limited to platinum-based

89
00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:14.160
chemotherapy, such as cisplatin.

90
00:05:14.340 --> 00:05:16.140
However, the responses are very short-lived.

91
00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:19.960
There has been no effective targeted therapies designed for this disease, and

92
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.760
therefore, there is still an urgent need to understand the molecular mechanism

93
00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:25.840
driving the NEPC development and aggressiveness.

94
00:05:27.540 --> 00:05:30.880
So to study NEPC, our labs established a unique platform,

95
00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:32.680
321-321 RPDX model.

96
00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:37.410
So after the castration in the host 321, the model fully

97
00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:41.220
recapitulates the entire transition from adenoma to NEPC, which

98
00:05:41.280 --> 00:05:43.380
is also observed in the original patient.

99
00:05:44.020 --> 00:05:47.410
So using this model, we are able to collect samples from different time

100
00:05:47.500 --> 00:05:51.150
points and conduct longitudinal analyses to examine the cellular and

101
00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:55.020
molecular modifications across different stages of the transition.

102
00:05:56.940 --> 00:06:00.720
So extensive research by our lab and other study groups has pointed out a

103
00:06:00.780 --> 00:06:04.330
significant role of epigenetic regulation in driving this transdifferentiation

104
00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:08.244
process.In particular, unlike adenocarcinoma, NEPC

105
00:06:08.284 --> 00:06:10.724
cells exhibit a salt-and-pepper chromatin pattern,

106
00:06:12.004 --> 00:06:15.484
which suggests that chromatin modification occurred during this process.

107
00:06:16.464 --> 00:06:19.884
And a key component influencing this chromatin landscape modification

108
00:06:20.444 --> 00:06:24.424
is the activity of chromatin remodelers, which modify the structure and

109
00:06:24.464 --> 00:06:28.324
positioning of the nucleosomes, and thereby modulating the chromatin landscape

110
00:06:28.384 --> 00:06:29.464
and the downstream pathways.

111
00:06:30.764 --> 00:06:34.224
However, the key remodelers driving the NEPC still remain largely unknown.

112
00:06:35.144 --> 00:06:39.044
And therefore, in this study, we aim to identify the key remodelers for driving

113
00:06:39.084 --> 00:06:40.644
NEPC development and aggressiveness.

114
00:06:41.124 --> 00:06:45.104
We hypothesize that chromatin remodelers activate early and sustain during the

115
00:06:45.144 --> 00:06:49.044
entire NEPC progression, function as an upstream regulator that drives not

116
00:06:49.104 --> 00:06:52.984
only NE lineage transition, but also the maintenance of aggressive phenotypes in

117
00:06:53.024 --> 00:06:56.964
the terminal EPC. Importantly, targeting these remodelers and/or

118
00:06:56.984 --> 00:07:00.944
their downstream factors may provide better therapeutic opportunities.

119
00:07:02.864 --> 00:07:06.843
So to identify the candidate chromatin remodeler, we perform

120
00:07:07.044 --> 00:07:10.924
longitudinal transcriptomic analysis on samples collected from

121
00:07:10.984 --> 00:07:14.004
three different time points. So pre-castration,

122
00:07:14.584 --> 00:07:18.394
post-castration 12 weeks, which is the early stage of NEPC development, and

123
00:07:18.424 --> 00:07:22.144
relapse 331H. So we first look into the 82 genes

124
00:07:23.044 --> 00:07:27.024
and identify the upregulated remodelers in the

125
00:07:27.064 --> 00:07:29.784
terminal EPC by comparing 331H to 31.

126
00:07:30.464 --> 00:07:33.944
And then we further compare the upregulated genes in the post-castration 12 weeks

127
00:07:34.124 --> 00:07:36.904
to 331H to identify the ones that could be induced early.

128
00:07:37.804 --> 00:07:41.424
And CHD7 emerged as the study candidate by showing progressive

129
00:07:41.504 --> 00:07:44.624
activation and high sustained expression in the terminal EPC.

130
00:07:46.804 --> 00:07:50.764
So to validate our finding, we examine CHD7 expression along with

131
00:07:50.824 --> 00:07:54.584
adenome and NE lineage markers on the protein level across three phases.

132
00:07:55.364 --> 00:07:58.964
And what we observe is that consistent with RNA-seq data, CHD7

133
00:07:59.004 --> 00:08:02.664
expression is minimal in the pre-castration and induced early at the

134
00:08:02.784 --> 00:08:06.754
post-castration 12 weeks. However, at this stage, AR signaling has been shut down,

135
00:08:07.764 --> 00:08:09.554
but NE lineage has yet to show up.

136
00:08:10.544 --> 00:08:13.984
Importantly, CHD7 expression continues to increase and highly

137
00:08:14.023 --> 00:08:17.624
sustains in the terminal EPC where NE lineage has

138
00:08:17.684 --> 00:08:18.304
established.

139
00:08:19.384 --> 00:08:23.244
All these results together indicate that CHD7 is an early event of the

140
00:08:23.264 --> 00:08:24.104
NEPC development.

141
00:08:25.364 --> 00:08:29.204
So to assess its clinical relevance, we look into the clinical

142
00:08:29.324 --> 00:08:33.124
samples and consistent with our data, that

143
00:08:33.144 --> 00:08:36.804
CHD7 upper regulations is consistently observed in EPC tumors,

144
00:08:37.704 --> 00:08:41.475
indicating that CHD7 is not only an early event, but also highly

145
00:08:41.584 --> 00:08:44.204
sustained and clinical relevant to the terminal NEPC.

146
00:08:46.344 --> 00:08:49.964
So as CHD7 is an early event, we next investigated whether

147
00:08:50.024 --> 00:08:52.664
CHD7 could promote this transdifferentiation process.

148
00:08:53.404 --> 00:08:56.984
So to do so, we first overexpressed the gene in the adenoma cell line and

149
00:08:57.184 --> 00:09:00.124
treated the cells with AR targeted therapy.

150
00:09:00.164 --> 00:09:03.524
And what we observe is that overexpression of the genes lead to increased

151
00:09:03.544 --> 00:09:07.304
expression of NE markers and transcription factors, suggesting that CHD7

152
00:09:07.344 --> 00:09:10.344
upregulation leads to the transdifferentiation.

153
00:09:11.344 --> 00:09:14.964
On the other side, the knockdown of the gene leads to reduced NE marker and

154
00:09:14.984 --> 00:09:18.624
transcription factor expression, indicating that CHD7

155
00:09:18.664 --> 00:09:22.204
contributes to the maintenance of the NE phenotype in the terminal EPC as well.

156
00:09:23.644 --> 00:09:27.204
So to further define how CHD7 shapes the

157
00:09:28.184 --> 00:09:31.624
chromatin landscape as a chromatin remodeler, we perform

158
00:09:31.704 --> 00:09:34.404
ATAC-seq in the control and the knockdown cells.

159
00:09:35.264 --> 00:09:38.924
And what we observe is that knockdown of the gene preferentially

160
00:09:38.964 --> 00:09:42.444
contributed to a global shift toward a closing state.

161
00:09:42.604 --> 00:09:46.204
And then to further understand whether these modifications are directly mediated by

162
00:09:46.224 --> 00:09:46.884
CHD7,

163
00:09:47.764 --> 00:09:51.484
we integrated the data with CHD7 ChIP-seq in the

164
00:09:51.504 --> 00:09:55.384
control cells, and we observed 94% of the CHD7

165
00:09:55.444 --> 00:09:59.384
bound regions with modified accessibility are predominantly

166
00:09:59.444 --> 00:10:02.584
lost accessibility, which indicates that CHD7 directly

167
00:10:02.624 --> 00:10:05.864
maintains the chromatin state at its binding sites.

168
00:10:07.244 --> 00:10:10.804
Importantly, these regions corresponded to 1805 genes, which

169
00:10:10.864 --> 00:10:12.464
CHD7 can directly regulate.

170
00:10:13.684 --> 00:10:15.784
So to understand the functional consequences

171
00:10:16.644 --> 00:10:20.384
of CHD7-mediated chromatin accessibility, we integrated the

172
00:10:20.424 --> 00:10:24.324
data of 1805 genes with downregulated genes observed

173
00:10:24.403 --> 00:10:28.004
in the RNA-seq, and we identified 563

174
00:10:28.104 --> 00:10:32.004
genes as a direct set of CHD7 direct transcriptional targets.

175
00:10:33.284 --> 00:10:36.684
Furthermore, the pathway enrichment analysis indicate strong

176
00:10:36.804 --> 00:10:40.524
enrichment in the neural fate commitment, DNA replication, and the cell

177
00:10:40.584 --> 00:10:44.464
cycle progression. As we look into the pathways, the

178
00:10:44.484 --> 00:10:48.144
heat map shows key representative targets, including a lineage transcription factor

179
00:10:48.324 --> 00:10:50.154
such as ASCL1, SOX1, and

180
00:10:51.464 --> 00:10:54.984
also replication stress machinery, including RPA and RFC

181
00:10:55.064 --> 00:10:58.704
components. All these results indicate that CHD7 directly

182
00:10:58.984 --> 00:11:02.714
orchestrates transcription programs governing lineage identity and

183
00:11:02.844 --> 00:11:04.124
also replication competence.

184
00:11:06.024 --> 00:11:09.444
Then we proceeded to validate those insights

185
00:11:09.624 --> 00:11:13.444
functionally, and we observed that knockdown of the gene significantly reduced the

186
00:11:13.464 --> 00:11:16.384
cell growth and DNA synthesis. Additionally,

187
00:11:17.344 --> 00:11:21.004
DNA damage has been accumulating, and also

188
00:11:21.404 --> 00:11:22.964
apoptosis has been increased as well.

189
00:11:25.904 --> 00:11:29.664
Indeed, while knockdown of the gene impaired DNA replication, the concurrent

190
00:11:29.724 --> 00:11:33.024
accumulation of the DNA damage indicate that there's unresolved

191
00:11:33.304 --> 00:11:34.504
replication-associated stress.

192
00:11:35.144 --> 00:11:36.444
And efficient resolution of

193
00:11:37.284 --> 00:11:40.644
such stress requires activation of ATR checkpoint,

194
00:11:41.364 --> 00:11:45.144
which also relies on the replication stress sensory machinery, including

195
00:11:45.224 --> 00:11:49.104
RPA and RFC components. However, these components has been disrupted

196
00:11:49.124 --> 00:11:53.024
by CHD7 transcriptionally, and therefore, in this part, we hypothesize

197
00:11:53.034 --> 00:11:56.544
that CHD7 is required for efficient ATR

198
00:11:56.584 --> 00:12:00.364
checkpoint activation during this NEPC progression.

199
00:12:02.244 --> 00:12:06.164
Indeed, once we knock down the gene, what we observe is that although the

200
00:12:06.204 --> 00:12:09.864
protein level of ATR and checkpoint remains unchanged, however,

201
00:12:09.964 --> 00:12:13.648
phosphorylated form of these two genes are significantly reducedThis

202
00:12:13.728 --> 00:12:17.468
indicates that the knockdown of the gene really impairs the ATR checkpoint activity

203
00:12:17.528 --> 00:12:18.468
in the NEPC cells.

204
00:12:20.188 --> 00:12:24.008
So based on these mechanistic insights, we look into whether

205
00:12:24.068 --> 00:12:27.148
this axis has any kind of implications in the

206
00:12:27.168 --> 00:12:30.008
therapeutic response, in particular to the cisplatin.

207
00:12:30.888 --> 00:12:34.448
As cisplatin induces DNA crosslinks and therefore will lead into

208
00:12:34.548 --> 00:12:35.408
replication stress,

209
00:12:36.248 --> 00:12:39.608
we wanted to see whether cisplatin would enhance CHD7

210
00:12:39.648 --> 00:12:43.498
expression and also boost the ATR checkpoint activity, and

211
00:12:43.568 --> 00:12:47.068
whether targeting this axis can sensitize the NEPC cells to the

212
00:12:47.108 --> 00:12:47.608
cisplatin.

213
00:12:48.888 --> 00:12:52.748
So upon the cisplatin treatment, we observed a progress

214
00:12:52.908 --> 00:12:56.348
increase in the CHD7 expression and also the ATR checkpoint

215
00:12:56.408 --> 00:13:00.188
activity. And then to see whether this axis contributes to this drug

216
00:13:00.288 --> 00:13:04.208
response functionally, we treated the cells

217
00:13:04.308 --> 00:13:08.188
in control and knockdown cells and observed that IC50 of the cisplatin

218
00:13:08.248 --> 00:13:11.068
is greatly reduced. This indicates that the knockdown

219
00:13:12.128 --> 00:13:13.988
increased the sensitivity to the cisplatin.

220
00:13:16.388 --> 00:13:19.918
However, there has been no approved drugs for

221
00:13:20.228 --> 00:13:24.008
CHD7, and therefore, we proposed to see whether the downstream

222
00:13:24.108 --> 00:13:27.968
effector checkpoint inhibition could enhance the cisplatin response in

223
00:13:28.008 --> 00:13:29.128
the NEPC cells.

224
00:13:30.048 --> 00:13:33.828
So we first validated the effective checkpoint inhibition in the

225
00:13:33.848 --> 00:13:37.288
cells using the inhibitor, and then we proceed to combine

226
00:13:37.348 --> 00:13:39.968
cisplatin with the checkpoint inhibition.

227
00:13:40.008 --> 00:13:43.568
And what we observed is that the combination leads to increased DNA

228
00:13:43.588 --> 00:13:45.728
accumulation and also apoptosis.

229
00:13:46.328 --> 00:13:50.268
Consistent with that, the cell viability is greatly reduced with the combination

230
00:13:50.348 --> 00:13:51.908
compared to either treatment alone.

231
00:13:56.128 --> 00:13:59.208
So overall, we identify CHD7 as an early

232
00:13:59.708 --> 00:14:03.688
regulator and is really highly relevant to the clinical NEPC.

233
00:14:04.288 --> 00:14:08.168
We examined that it promotes NE differentiation process

234
00:14:08.228 --> 00:14:11.788
and also regulates NE phenotype proliferation and survival in the terminal

235
00:14:11.828 --> 00:14:12.388
NEPC.

236
00:14:13.528 --> 00:14:17.148
Mechanistically, we look into that CHD7 directly regulates

237
00:14:17.188 --> 00:14:20.708
chromatin accessibility and sustain the transcriptional programs

238
00:14:20.948 --> 00:14:24.628
underlying the lineage identity and replication competence.

239
00:14:25.148 --> 00:14:28.628
And also the gene enables efficient ATR checkpoint

240
00:14:29.068 --> 00:14:32.988
activation under replication stress, and therefore this axis mediates

241
00:14:33.048 --> 00:14:34.068
the cisplatin tolerance.

242
00:14:35.628 --> 00:14:39.348
And for that, I want to thank everybody for attending, thank my supervisor, my

243
00:14:39.668 --> 00:14:42.488
lab members, and open to any questions.

244
00:14:47.188 --> 00:14:47.788
Questions?

245
00:14:49.768 --> 00:14:53.388
Okay. I will start. Great talk. I wanted to ask, what controls

246
00:14:53.428 --> 00:14:56.058
mechanistically the expression of CHD7?

247
00:14:57.668 --> 00:14:59.528
So right now, we haven't

248
00:15:00.528 --> 00:15:04.288
defined the specific upstream regulator for CHD7,

249
00:15:04.428 --> 00:15:08.088
but we do have plenty results to suggest that they're not

250
00:15:08.128 --> 00:15:12.068
directly regulated by AR, because we do have

251
00:15:13.988 --> 00:15:17.718
