574
00:34:12.361 --> 00:34:16.301
I would like to talk to you today about my project entitled "Promoter Methylation

575
00:34:16.400 --> 00:34:19.640
Gains in Aging and Cancer Are Independent of Replication."

576
00:34:21.380 --> 00:34:23.580
I have no financial relationships to disclose.

577
00:34:25.821 --> 00:34:26.660
There are

578
00:34:27.640 --> 00:34:28.261
multiple

579
00:34:29.321 --> 00:34:33.281
levels of chromatin remodelers that exist to

580
00:34:34.261 --> 00:34:35.960
mediate DNA methylation,

581
00:34:36.761 --> 00:34:38.761
for example, in aging and colon cancer.

582
00:34:39.781 --> 00:34:43.620
If we take young wild-type organoids, we culture them for 12 to 14

583
00:34:43.640 --> 00:34:46.060
months, they become old wild-type organoids.

584
00:34:46.600 --> 00:34:50.440
We induce a BRF600E mutation. Within two weeks, they will become a colon

585
00:34:50.500 --> 00:34:54.460
cancer. If we take young wild-type organoids, culture them

586
00:34:54.500 --> 00:34:58.320
with the BRF600E mutation for five months, they will also become a colon

587
00:34:58.380 --> 00:35:02.020
cancer. We can short-circuit this process if we knock out these

588
00:35:02.090 --> 00:35:03.080
four key genes,

589
00:35:04.020 --> 00:35:07.990
induce a BRF mutation, and then within two weeks, they will become a colon cancer.

590
00:35:08.600 --> 00:35:12.200
And what's interesting about all of these models is they all

591
00:35:12.240 --> 00:35:16.120
share a high degree of DNA methylation

592
00:35:16.200 --> 00:35:19.780
alterations. So this begets the following questions.

593
00:35:20.220 --> 00:35:23.680
What are the dynamics of DNA methylation during early tumorigenesis?

594
00:35:24.200 --> 00:35:27.240
Are the DNA methylation changes induced by oncogenic stress?

595
00:35:27.680 --> 00:35:30.310
And are the DNA methylation changes due to cell division?

596
00:35:32.220 --> 00:35:34.980
To examine this, we follow the following experimental outline.

597
00:35:35.720 --> 00:35:39.560
From the mice, we take its colon, we develop it into organoids, and

598
00:35:39.600 --> 00:35:42.100
then we induce the BRF600E mutation.

599
00:35:42.210 --> 00:35:46.060
And then monthly for five months, we disassociate the organoid into single

600
00:35:46.140 --> 00:35:50.080
cells, grow the single cell into the single organoid, pick the single organoid,

601
00:35:50.210 --> 00:35:53.940
and do a single organoid WGBS. Because this is a single organoid,

602
00:35:54.520 --> 00:35:57.980
we need to alter the WGBS library prep a little bit.

603
00:35:58.260 --> 00:36:01.560
In order to do this, we use whole genome amplification that is

604
00:36:01.580 --> 00:36:05.260
multime-based, using multiple displacement amplification to

605
00:36:05.340 --> 00:36:08.820
combat primer bias and amplification bias.

606
00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:14.380
If we look at the resulting data, what we can observe is that the control

607
00:36:14.460 --> 00:36:17.900
lineage exhibits a stepwise divergence from one to five months.

608
00:36:18.360 --> 00:36:22.180
The BRF lineage, however, exhibits epigenetic drift, followed by

609
00:36:22.240 --> 00:36:24.700
clonal convergence or takeover at the five months.

610
00:36:25.480 --> 00:36:28.360
Interestingly, if we compare global CPG

611
00:36:28.400 --> 00:36:32.084
methylationBetween control and BRAF V600E

612
00:36:32.144 --> 00:36:32.484
clones,

613
00:36:33.344 --> 00:36:36.444
we do not see any global DNA methylation changes,

614
00:36:37.044 --> 00:36:40.664
indicating that BRAF V600E does not acutely induce DNA

615
00:36:40.674 --> 00:36:42.904
methylation changes in our colon organoids.

616
00:36:43.624 --> 00:36:47.164
If we look at our differential methylation, what we observe is areas

617
00:36:47.204 --> 00:36:50.884
without CGI tend to lose methylation.

618
00:36:51.344 --> 00:36:53.464
Areas with CGI tend to gain methylation.

619
00:36:53.804 --> 00:36:55.384
This is consistent with the literature.

620
00:36:56.104 --> 00:36:59.904
If we look at the percentage of overlap between the

621
00:36:59.924 --> 00:37:03.784
two lineages in terms of gain or in terms of loss, there is very little

622
00:37:03.864 --> 00:37:05.684
overlap in terms of the sites affected.

623
00:37:06.564 --> 00:37:09.944
However, if I was to map those specific CpG sites to their

624
00:37:09.984 --> 00:37:10.804
associated

625
00:37:11.704 --> 00:37:15.344
genomic elements, for example, promoter with CGI, promoter without

626
00:37:15.384 --> 00:37:18.664
CGI, what we observe is that there is a vast overlap

627
00:37:19.524 --> 00:37:23.144
in areas affected. To investigate this further, we looked

628
00:37:23.304 --> 00:37:27.164
at our single-cell RNA seq. We did a pseudobulk analysis,

629
00:37:27.604 --> 00:37:31.444
and we enriched for unique transcription factors in those differentially

630
00:37:31.484 --> 00:37:35.044
methylated sites. What we observed is that control lineage

631
00:37:35.063 --> 00:37:38.864
transcription factors are enriched for stress or viral-related

632
00:37:38.944 --> 00:37:40.484
pathways. But those are

633
00:37:41.324 --> 00:37:44.804
not present in the BRAF V600E unique

634
00:37:44.824 --> 00:37:47.704
transcription factors. Instead, we have an enrichment for

635
00:37:48.084 --> 00:37:50.944
cancer-related transcription factors.

636
00:37:51.004 --> 00:37:54.744
So this indicates some sort of

637
00:37:54.784 --> 00:37:58.084
invasion strategy in the BRAF V600E

638
00:37:59.324 --> 00:38:01.724
lineage, but that has to be further investigated.

639
00:38:02.644 --> 00:38:06.564
So far, I've talked to you about the one-month and the five-month comparison.

640
00:38:06.684 --> 00:38:09.844
However, I also have a two-month, a three-month, and a four-month comparison.

641
00:38:10.944 --> 00:38:14.464
In order to investigate whether our methylation gains were

642
00:38:14.504 --> 00:38:17.004
stochastic or formed any sort of trajectory,

643
00:38:18.124 --> 00:38:21.474
we looked at bivalent CGI elements, and we also looked at

644
00:38:21.504 --> 00:38:25.404
non-CGI elements. Bivalent because they have been shown to gain as a function of

645
00:38:25.444 --> 00:38:29.364
replication, and non-CGI because they have been shown to lose as a function of

646
00:38:29.424 --> 00:38:30.124
replication.

647
00:38:31.044 --> 00:38:34.764
What we observe is that the BRAF and the control lineage

648
00:38:35.384 --> 00:38:38.564
exhibit very similar trajectories across the five months.

649
00:38:39.184 --> 00:38:42.604
We do not see an accelerated trajectory in the BRAF lineage,

650
00:38:43.164 --> 00:38:46.944
which would have been expected if those DNA methylation gains were a function

651
00:38:47.144 --> 00:38:50.404
of replication. However, we do see an accelerated

652
00:38:50.424 --> 00:38:54.084
trajectory in the BRAF lineage in non-CGI sites,

653
00:38:54.504 --> 00:38:55.984
indicating that the losses in

654
00:38:56.804 --> 00:38:59.544
DNA methylation are a function of replication.

655
00:39:00.784 --> 00:39:04.444
If we look at this in external datasets, for example, in this

656
00:39:04.484 --> 00:39:07.964
transformation model, where you have early passage cells

657
00:39:08.484 --> 00:39:12.004
that are then serially transfected with different proliferative

658
00:39:12.044 --> 00:39:15.784
agents, what you observe is median methylation remains constant no

659
00:39:15.844 --> 00:39:18.904
matter how many proliferative agents are added.

660
00:39:19.634 --> 00:39:23.504
And then if you look at the non-CGI sites in this particular experiment,

661
00:39:23.644 --> 00:39:27.164
what you observe is a downward trajectory in terms of DNA methylation,

662
00:39:27.664 --> 00:39:31.584
indicating, again, that your gains in methylation at your bivalently marked

663
00:39:31.664 --> 00:39:34.624
