1074
01:03:18.624 --> 01:03:22.304
Our next speaker is Joshua Luepe from Van

1075
01:03:22.424 --> 01:03:25.444
Andel Institute, and he's going to talk about DNA

1076
01:03:25.504 --> 01:03:29.364
methyltransferase 1 and its application in cancer

1077
01:03:29.424 --> 01:03:29.864
therapy.

1078
01:03:34.844 --> 01:03:35.124
Hi.

1079
01:03:38.344 --> 01:03:42.164
I'd like to thank the organizers for giving me this chance to share my work

1080
01:03:42.204 --> 01:03:42.804
with you all.

1081
01:03:43.624 --> 01:03:46.864
I'm Joshua, and I'll be talking today about

1082
01:03:48.064 --> 01:03:52.024
targeting the ubiquitin reading function of DNMT1 as a

1083
01:03:52.044 --> 01:03:55.444
next generation approach for epigenetic cancer

1084
01:03:55.484 --> 01:03:56.044
therapy.

1085
01:03:58.644 --> 01:04:02.184
Aberrant or abnormal DNA methylation is mediated

1086
01:04:02.244 --> 01:04:04.204
through DNA methyltransferases,

1087
01:04:05.024 --> 01:04:08.884
and this abnormal DNA methylation is one of the

1088
01:04:08.944 --> 01:04:12.684
most consistent and functionally important epigenetic

1089
01:04:12.764 --> 01:04:14.444
alterations in cancer.

1090
01:04:15.244 --> 01:04:15.664
And

1091
01:04:16.804 --> 01:04:20.644
some of its effect include tumor suppressor gene silencing,

1092
01:04:20.724 --> 01:04:22.064
as well as oncogene silencing.

1093
01:04:22.864 --> 01:04:26.544
It also results in hypomethylation of these

1094
01:04:26.584 --> 01:04:29.484
oncogenic regions, resulting in genomic instability.

1095
01:04:30.584 --> 01:04:34.244
This effect is not only localized, but it impacts

1096
01:04:34.504 --> 01:04:37.964
nearly all the hallmarks of

1097
01:04:38.884 --> 01:04:42.264
cancers, from sustaining proliferative

1098
01:04:42.364 --> 01:04:46.004
signaling to evading growth suppressors to even immune

1099
01:04:46.064 --> 01:04:49.624
modulation. So for this reason, DNA

1100
01:04:49.664 --> 01:04:53.424
methyltransferase inhibitors are developed to clinically

1101
01:04:54.004 --> 01:04:55.284
manage cancers.

1102
01:04:56.984 --> 01:04:59.884
Agents such as 5-Azacytidine and

1103
01:04:59.964 --> 01:05:03.544
Decitabine are the most clinically advanced

1104
01:05:03.684 --> 01:05:07.564
epigenetic drugs currently. And despite their successes

1105
01:05:07.724 --> 01:05:09.064
in hematological

1106
01:05:10.344 --> 01:05:14.284
cancers, they do have

1107
01:05:14.324 --> 01:05:18.064
limitations, especially or in particular with solid tumors.

1108
01:05:18.684 --> 01:05:19.044
And

1109
01:05:20.404 --> 01:05:24.124
their limitations include the fact that they have a short half-life,

1110
01:05:24.244 --> 01:05:27.984
mainly because of cytidine deaminase that is able to

1111
01:05:28.064 --> 01:05:31.424
inactivate them. They're also replication

1112
01:05:31.464 --> 01:05:35.204
dependent. And then there's the issue of dose limiting toxicities.

1113
01:05:36.484 --> 01:05:39.584
The mechanism of action of these drugs requires

1114
01:05:41.024 --> 01:05:44.824
chromatin targeting of DNA methyltransferases.

1115
01:05:45.344 --> 01:05:48.804
And for DNMT1, it involves the E3

1116
01:05:48.844 --> 01:05:50.604
ligase UHRF1.

1117
01:05:52.334 --> 01:05:56.054
DNMT1 relies on this co-factor, UHRF1,

1118
01:05:56.724 --> 01:06:00.344
in order to carry out faithful methylation inheritance.

1119
01:06:00.804 --> 01:06:03.864
As you can see from this figure on the left, in the absence of

1120
01:06:03.944 --> 01:06:07.844
UHRF1, there is a global reduction in DNA methylation.

1121
01:06:08.764 --> 01:06:12.584
Also, DNMT1 is unable to localize to

1122
01:06:12.604 --> 01:06:15.704
replicating foci in the absence of UHRF1.

1123
01:06:16.264 --> 01:06:19.564
This suggests that DNMT1 targeting to chromatin

1124
01:06:20.164 --> 01:06:23.424
is replication coupled and also UHRF1

1125
01:06:24.504 --> 01:06:28.344
dependent. So then the question is: how does UHRF1 carry out

1126
01:06:28.364 --> 01:06:31.783
this process of targeting DNMT1 to

1127
01:06:31.864 --> 01:06:32.444
chromatin?

1128
01:06:34.624 --> 01:06:38.604
Through multivalent interactions that UHRF1 has with DNA

1129
01:06:38.664 --> 01:06:41.004
and histone H3, it is

1130
01:06:42.344 --> 01:06:45.574
targeted to newly replicated DNA, where through

1131
01:06:45.624 --> 01:06:49.284
its ring finger domain, it's able to write the

1132
01:06:49.304 --> 01:06:51.734
ubiquitin marks on the histone H3 tails.

1133
01:06:52.334 --> 01:06:55.964
DNMT1 then recognizes these ubiquitin marks through

1134
01:06:56.024 --> 01:06:59.804
its ubiquitin interacting motifs that are located or embedded

1135
01:06:59.844 --> 01:07:03.008
within its RFTS domain.Once this happens,

1136
01:07:03.128 --> 01:07:07.048
DNMT1 becomes recruited, and it's able to

1137
01:07:07.148 --> 01:07:10.828
lay or write the methylation marks on the daughter strand.

1138
01:07:12.028 --> 01:07:15.518
So the UIMs or the ubiquitin interacting motifs of

1139
01:07:15.548 --> 01:07:19.428
DNMT1, therefore present to us a novel way of

1140
01:07:19.488 --> 01:07:21.268
targeting DNMT1.

1141
01:07:22.268 --> 01:07:23.628
So we asked the question,

1142
01:07:24.448 --> 01:07:27.588
could the ubiquitin interacting motif of DNMT1

1143
01:07:28.708 --> 01:07:32.688
be responsible for the DNA methylation maintenance function of

1144
01:07:32.728 --> 01:07:36.548
DNMT1? So to answer this question, we built a

1145
01:07:36.568 --> 01:07:39.758
genetic complementation system where we could

1146
01:07:41.508 --> 01:07:45.388
sustain a colorectal cancer cell in the absence of

1147
01:07:45.668 --> 01:07:49.528
key functional domains of DNMT1. So what we basically

1148
01:07:49.548 --> 01:07:53.008
did was to mutate the catalytic domain and

1149
01:07:53.108 --> 01:07:56.368
also the UIM domains, and then we compared them.

1150
01:07:56.988 --> 01:08:00.728
And in vitro assays that we carried out in our

1151
01:08:00.788 --> 01:08:04.208
lab show that the UIM is unable to

1152
01:08:04.348 --> 01:08:04.868
bind

1153
01:08:05.768 --> 01:08:09.628
ubiquitinated nucleosomes, even though it was able to retain

1154
01:08:09.688 --> 01:08:13.488
its catalytic activity. And when we measured the

1155
01:08:14.948 --> 01:08:16.728
DNA methylation profile from the

1156
01:08:17.829 --> 01:08:18.489
mutated

1157
01:08:19.449 --> 01:08:23.348
UIMs, we found that the loss of methylation

1158
01:08:23.568 --> 01:08:26.788
with the UIM mutant is comparable or

1159
01:08:26.888 --> 01:08:30.318
identical to DNMT1 being knocked down or they're

1160
01:08:30.348 --> 01:08:34.008
catalytically dead. So from this, we also performed

1161
01:08:34.048 --> 01:08:37.508
cell-based assays. We did clonogenic assays as well as

1162
01:08:37.548 --> 01:08:38.208
IncuCyte

1163
01:08:39.348 --> 01:08:42.909
outgrowth assays. And we also found that in the absence of a

1164
01:08:42.949 --> 01:08:46.768
functional ubiquitin interacting motif, cell viability is

1165
01:08:46.848 --> 01:08:50.588
also hampered in a similar way as what we see with the catalytically

1166
01:08:50.668 --> 01:08:54.468
dead or DNMT1 being knocked down. So from this, we concluded that

1167
01:08:54.869 --> 01:08:58.768
DNMT1's ubiquitin reading function is essential for DNA

1168
01:08:58.808 --> 01:09:02.008
methylation and also the viability of cancer cells.

1169
01:09:03.608 --> 01:09:07.268
Next, we then asked, transcriptionally, what happens when this

1170
01:09:07.348 --> 01:09:08.768
UIM is non-functional?

1171
01:09:09.728 --> 01:09:13.168
And then we compared that with DNMT1 knockdown, as well as the

1172
01:09:13.188 --> 01:09:16.168
catalytically dead. And we found there were significant

1173
01:09:16.208 --> 01:09:19.538
overlaps between these, and this is

1174
01:09:19.608 --> 01:09:23.568
because, importantly, what we see is that these genes are

1175
01:09:23.608 --> 01:09:27.508
upregulated, and when we looked at their promoters, we

1176
01:09:27.568 --> 01:09:31.228
see that they are losing DNA methylation, which is

1177
01:09:31.268 --> 01:09:35.088
consistent with what I just showed on the previous slide, that the UIMs

1178
01:09:35.148 --> 01:09:38.468
are needed for the DNA methylation function of

1179
01:09:38.489 --> 01:09:42.248
DNMT1. So we also looked at, globally, which

1180
01:09:42.288 --> 01:09:45.568
pathways are being changed as a result of a non-functional

1181
01:09:46.029 --> 01:09:48.449
ubiquitin interacting motif of DNMT1.

1182
01:09:48.968 --> 01:09:52.928
And we do see upregulation of viral mimicry associated

1183
01:09:53.008 --> 01:09:56.668
hallmarks and a downregulation of oncogenic transmitomic

1184
01:09:56.768 --> 01:10:00.388
pathways. And these pathways are also

1185
01:10:00.428 --> 01:10:03.768
consistent with what we observe with decitabine or the

1186
01:10:03.848 --> 01:10:07.428
current FDA-approved DNMTis.

1187
01:10:08.008 --> 01:10:09.978
So from this, we actually

1188
01:10:11.408 --> 01:10:15.088
concluded that the DNMT1 ubiquitin reader disruption is

1189
01:10:15.128 --> 01:10:18.128
able to recapitulate the effects of

1190
01:10:18.168 --> 01:10:22.148
DNMTis. So this presents us with a novel way

1191
01:10:22.208 --> 01:10:26.148
of targeting DNMT1. So this motivated

1192
01:10:26.228 --> 01:10:29.648
us to perform two screens. The first was a natural

1193
01:10:29.748 --> 01:10:30.648
product and

1194
01:10:31.848 --> 01:10:35.008
macrocyclic compound screen, which we did in

1195
01:10:35.048 --> 01:10:38.518
collaboration with the University of Michigan Center for Chemical

1196
01:10:38.588 --> 01:10:42.348
Genomics. And from this screen, we identified a natural product

1197
01:10:42.448 --> 01:10:45.728
extract with afetinib Pharmaco four as a hit.

1198
01:10:46.568 --> 01:10:50.368
We also did a biologic screen where we used

1199
01:10:50.468 --> 01:10:54.088
de novo design tools to engineer small protein

1200
01:10:54.168 --> 01:10:57.568
binders that could actually competitively bind to the

1201
01:10:57.648 --> 01:11:01.028
UIMs of DNMT1 to prevent its ubiquitin reading

1202
01:11:01.068 --> 01:11:04.918
activity. And what we found from the preliminary screens was

1203
01:11:04.968 --> 01:11:08.888
we're able to identify a low nanomolar binder, which is able

1204
01:11:08.968 --> 01:11:12.088
to inhibit DNMT1's ubiquitin reading function.

1205
01:11:13.208 --> 01:11:17.178
And we are excited about these particular binders, and we're looking

1206
01:11:17.288 --> 01:11:17.847
forward to

1207
01:11:19.448 --> 01:11:22.928
pursue these as a novel way of targeting DNMT1.

1208
01:11:23.448 --> 01:11:26.668
So to sum up my talk, the methyltransferase activity of

1209
01:11:26.708 --> 01:11:30.608
DNMT1 in human cancer cells is completely dependent on its ability

1210
01:11:30.628 --> 01:11:34.368
to read ubiquitin activity. And this ubiquitin

1211
01:11:34.408 --> 01:11:37.468
reading activity is also essential for the viability of these cancer cells.

1212
01:11:37.908 --> 01:11:41.248
And when it is disrupted, we see a strong hypomethylation,

1213
01:11:41.808 --> 01:11:45.768
activation of immune pathways, and a suppression of oncogenic signaling

1214
01:11:45.828 --> 01:11:49.668
pathways. And I've also shown you evidence that the

1215
01:11:49.708 --> 01:11:53.588
UIM motif or the ubiquitin reading activity of DNMT1 is

1216
01:11:53.628 --> 01:11:54.148
druggable.

