01:13:04.868 --> 01:13:08.696
Now we open to discussions and questions.So I can

1236
01:13:08.706 --> 01:13:12.696
start. This novel way of targeting DNMT1, how can it

1237
01:13:12.736 --> 01:13:16.666
be superior to the current target of therapies that we have for DNMT1,

1238
01:13:16.716 --> 01:13:20.356
and how does it look in mouse models, if you have done those

1239
01:13:20.376 --> 01:13:21.016
experiments?

1240
01:13:21.416 --> 01:13:21.716
Okay.

1241
01:13:22.616 --> 01:13:24.496
Let me start with the mouse models.

1242
01:13:24.976 --> 01:13:28.636
So the mouse models is one thing we are now looking to

1243
01:13:29.256 --> 01:13:31.296
start working on. We've applied for funding for that.

1244
01:13:31.356 --> 01:13:34.016
So that is something we have plans for.

1245
01:13:34.596 --> 01:13:37.876
And currently, we are testing these binders in

1246
01:13:38.796 --> 01:13:42.396
cell lines to see how it engages DNMT1, and whether it's able to

1247
01:13:42.436 --> 01:13:46.136
recapitulate what we've observed with the genetic manipulation of the

1248
01:13:46.216 --> 01:13:49.756
UIM domains. So how is this better than the

1249
01:13:49.816 --> 01:13:52.616
current DNMTis? For one,

1250
01:13:54.576 --> 01:13:57.396
what we've observed is that these are not replication-dependent.

1251
01:13:57.916 --> 01:14:00.785
Because the current DNMTis all need replication,

1252
01:14:01.196 --> 01:14:04.376
the DNA methyltransferases, to actually

1253
01:14:04.416 --> 01:14:08.376
be recruited to chromatin during replication for them to

1254
01:14:08.416 --> 01:14:10.566
carry out their functions. With this, all we're

1255
01:14:11.696 --> 01:14:15.536
inhibiting is the ability to recruit DNMT1 to chromatin.

1256
01:14:16.176 --> 01:14:17.276
So if we're able to

1257
01:14:18.116 --> 01:14:21.436
prevent that from happening, we will not need the replication

1258
01:14:22.816 --> 01:14:26.696
ability. And another issue with requiring replication is it

1259
01:14:26.756 --> 01:14:29.976
results in DNA damage, which can lead to a lot of off-target effects.

1260
01:14:30.436 --> 01:14:33.296
So we're still trying to refine these binders.

1261
01:14:33.716 --> 01:14:37.576
We've computationally generated them, and so we've used the one that came out

1262
01:14:37.636 --> 01:14:41.296
as a hit as the basis to iterate and get more

1263
01:14:41.316 --> 01:14:44.826
binders, which we're then going to screen till we get one that is

1264
01:14:45.136 --> 01:14:48.876
